he [[mangalica]] pigs.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/254840/Ruralni-Beograd-dve-trecine-prestonice|author=Dimitrije Bukvi\u0107|title= Ruralni Beograd - dve tre\u0107ine prestonice|date=14 April 2013| publisher= [[Politika]]|language=Serbian}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n19 people from Dudovica were killed in the Jasenovac Camp in the World War II. All were ethnic Serbs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cp13.heritagewebdesign.com/~lituchy/victim_search.php?field%3Dorigin%26searchtype%3Dcontains%26data%3Ddudovica |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-11-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711163926/https://cp13.heritagewebdesign.com/~lituchy/victim_search.php?field=origin&searchtype=contains&data=dudovica |archivedate=2011-07-11 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Dudovica}}\n*[http://www.maplandia.com/serbia-and-montenegro/srbija/dudovica/ Satellite map at Maplandia.com]\n\n[[Category:Suburbs of Belgrade]]\n[[Category:\u0160umadija]]\n[[Category:Lazarevac]]\n\n{{BelgradeRS-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Dewake", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dudovica"}
{"title_page": "Chase This Light", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use American English|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Chase This Light\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Jimmy Eat World]]\n| cover      = Chasethislight.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 16, 2007\n| recorded   = July 2006 \u2013 June 2007\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Alternative rock]]\n* [[emo]]\n* [[power pop]]\n* [[pop punk]]\n* [[pop rock]]\n}}\n| length     = 40:18\n| label      = [[Interscope Records|Interscope]]\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n* [[Jimmy Eat World]]\n* [[Christopher Mario Testa|Chris Testa]]\n* [[Butch Vig]]\n* [[John Fields (producer)|John Fields]] <small>(\"Here It Goes\")</small>\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Stay on My Side Tonight]]\n| prev_year  = 2005\n| next_title = [[Invented (album)|Invented]]\n| next_year  = 2010\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Chase This Light\n | type        = Studio\n | single1     = [[Big Casino]]\n | single1date = August 28, 2007\n | single2     = [[Always Be]]\n | single2date = December 3, 2007\n | single3     = Let It Happen\n | single3date = April 8, 2008\n}}\n}}\n'''''Chase This Light''''' is the sixth studio album by American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Jimmy Eat World]], released on October 16, 2007 by [[Interscope Records]]. The album was executive produced by [[Butch Vig]].\n\n==Recording==\nRecording for ''Chase This Light'' began in July 2006 with producer [[Butch Vig]]. In June 2007, it was announced that the album was being mixed by [[Chris Lord-Alge]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2131|title=Jimmy Eat World title new album, begin mixing|work=Alternative Press|date=June 5, 2007|accessdate=August 21, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160828101740/http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2131|archive-date=August 28, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\nThe song \"Carry You\" originated as a track from [[Jim Adkins]]' side project Go Big Casino.<ref>{{cite web|title=Has it really been 6 years?|url=http://gobigcasino.net/|work=Go Big Casino|publisher=GoBigCasino.net|accessdate=September 1, 2012|author=akatimo|date=May 27, 2012}}</ref><ref name=COS>{{cite web |author=Justin Gerber|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2013/06/dissected-jimmy-eat-world-with-jim-adkins/7/|title=Dissected: Jimmy Eat World (with Jim Adkins)|work=Consequence of Sound|page=7|accessdate=May 10, 2015}}</ref> Jimmy Eat World has recorded other Go Big Casino songs previously like \"[[Bleed American|Hear You Me]]\", \"[[Bleed American|My Sundown]]\", and \"Drugs or Me\".<ref>{{cite web|title=FAQ|url=http://gobigcasino.net/|work=GoBigCasino.net|publisher=GoBigCasino.net|accessdate=September 1, 2012|author=GoBigCasino.net|year=2004\u20132012}}</ref>\n\nAfter releasing \"Be Sensible\" as a B-Side, the band regretted not including it on the full album<ref>{{Citation|title=#41 - Zach and Holly Lind (The Wretched Desert, Jimmy Eat World)|url=https://open.spotify.com/episode/4ebCxWFka2AufHJKAVOqj4|language=en|access-date=2019-09-05}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nIn July 2007, the band went on a tour of the US, before doing several shows in South Africa as well as appearing at several festival dates in Europe the following month.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2295|title=Jimmy Eat World announce touring plans|work=Alternative Press|date=July 11, 2007|accessdate=August 25, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160828234349/http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2295|archive-date=August 28, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> On August 16, the album's track listing was revealed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2509|title=Jimmy Eat World reveal track listing|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=August 16, 2007|accessdate=March 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319023238/http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2509|archive-date=March 19, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> \"[[Big Casino]]\", the first single from the album, was released August 28 for download.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stereogum.com/6257/new_jimmy_eat_world_big_casino/video/|title=New Jimmy Eat World \u2013 \"Big Casino\"|work=Stereogum|accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref> The album's artwork was released the following day.<ref name=stereogumartwork>{{cite web|url=http://www.stereogum.com/6277/jimmy_eat_worlds_chase_this_light_album_art/news/|title=Jimmy Eat World's Chase This Light Album Art|work=Stereogum|accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref> In September and October, the group went on a North American tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2573|title=Jimmy Eat World to tour this fall|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=August 28, 2007|accessdate=March 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319022712/http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2573|archive-date=March 19, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''Chase This Light'' was released on October 16 through [[Interscope Records|Interscope]].<ref name=stereogumartwork/> A music video was released for \"Big Casino\" on October 24.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stereogum.com/6911/new_jimmy_eat_world_video_big_casino/video/|title=New Jimmy Eat World Video \u2013 \"Big Casino\"|work=Stereogum|accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref> \"[[Always Be (song)|Always Be]]\" began airing on various [[Radio channel#Audio|radio channels]] on December 3, 2007. In January 2008, the band supported [[Foo Fighters]] on a few US shows.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_3190|title=Jimmy Eat World to join Foo Fighters' 2008 U.S. tour|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=December 12, 2007|accessdate=July 8, 2017}}</ref> A music video for \"Always Be\" was released on January 29.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stereogum.com/7904/new_jimmy_eat_world_video_always_be/video/|title=New Jimmy Eat World Video \u2013 \"Always Be\"|work=Stereogum|accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref> From late January to early March, the band went on a tour of Europe and the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2938|title=Jimmy Eat World plan U.K./European tour for early 2008|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=November 2, 2007|accessdate=July 8, 2017}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> They were supported by [[Styrofoam (musician)|Styrofoam]] on the latter part of the tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_3422|title=Jimmy Eat World frontman sings on new Styrofoam song|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=January 31, 2008|accessdate=July 8, 2017}}{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In early April, the band appeared at the [[Bamboozle Left]] festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_3511|title=Blaqk Audio, Hot Water Music, H2O added to Bamboozle Left|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=February 15, 2008|accessdate=July 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728175351/http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_3511#|archive-date=July 28, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \"Let It Happen\" was released to radio on April 8.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allaccess.com/mail/archive/eweekly/alternative/2008-4-1.html|title=AllAccess.com Alternative eWeekly|work=AllAccess|date=April 1, 2008|accessdate=July 2, 2016}}</ref> In April and May, the band went on a co-headlining US tour with [[Paramore]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_3508|title=Jimmy Eat World/Paramore dates announced|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=February 15, 2008|accessdate=July 9, 2017}}{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In June and July, the band went on a tour of North America<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_3854|title=Jimmy Eat World schedule Canada/U.S. dates for July|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=May 13, 2008|accessdate=July 10, 2017}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> with support from [[Dear and the Headlights]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_4067|title=Dear And The Headlights announce dates, complete recording|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=June 12, 2008|accessdate=July 10, 2017}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical reception===\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = (66/100)<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/chase-this-light/jimmy-eat-world |title=Reviews for Chase This Light by Jimmy Eat World |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AbsolutePunk.net]] \n| rev1Score = (88%)<ref name=\"ABPunk\">{{cite web|last=Henderson |first=Steve |url=http://www.absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?t=271800 |title=Jimmy Eat World - Chase This Light - Album Review |publisher=AbsolutePunk.net |date=October 16, 2007 |accessdate=December 9, 2011 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120716112135/http://www.absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?t=271800 |archivedate=July 16, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref>\n| rev2 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web|last=Sendra |first=Tim |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/chase-this-light-mw0000486263 |title=Chase This Light - Jimmy Eat World |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=December 9, 2011}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3Score = A<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite magazine|last=Greenwald |first=Andy |url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20151945,00.html |title=Chase This Light Review |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |publisher=[[Time Inc.]] |date=October 12, 2007 |accessdate=December 9, 2011}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev4Score = (7/10)<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite magazine|last=Martin |first=Daniel |url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/jimmy-eat-world/9118 |title=NME Album Reviews - Jimmy Eat World |magazine=[[NME]] |publisher=[[IPC Media]] |date=October 19, 2007 |accessdate=December 9, 2011}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[PopMatters]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|5|10}}<ref name=\"PM\">{{cite web|last=Blackie |first=Andrew |url=https://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/jimmy-eat-world-chase-this-light/ |title=Jimmy Eat World: Chase This Light |website=[[PopMatters]] |date=October 16, 2007 |accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev6 = Rockfeedback\n| rev6Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Tomiak |first=Matt |url=http://www.rockfeedback.com/article.asp?nObjectID=5140 |title=Jimmy Eat World - Chase This Light |publisher=Rockfeedback |date=November 14, 2007 |accessdate=December 9, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090210064628/http://www.rockfeedback.com/article.asp?nObjectID=5140 |archivedate=February 10, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/16684805/review/16695742/chase_this_light |title=Chase This Light : Jimmy Eat World : Review |last=Hiatt |first=Brian |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |publisher=[[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media]] |date=October 18, 2007 |accessdate=April 4, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011024829/http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/16684805/review/16695742/chase_this_light |archivedate=October 11, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref>\n| rev8 = [[Slant Magazine]]\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"Slant\">{{cite web|last=Keefe |first=Jonathan |url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/jimmy-eat-world-chase-this-light/1198 |title=Jimmy Eat World: Chase This Light |publisher=[[Slant Magazine]] |date=October 15, 2007 |accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev9Score = (7/10)<ref name=\"Spin\">{{cite magazine|last=Beaujon |first=Andrew |url=https://www.spin.com/2007/11/jimmy-eat-world-chase-light-interscope/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090616152234/http://www.spin.com/reviews/jimmy-eat-world-chase-light-interscope|title=Jimmy Eat World, 'Chase This Light' (Interscope) |magazine=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |publisher=[[SpinMedia]] |date=November 1, 2007 |archivedate=June 16, 2009|accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev10 = [[Virgin Media]]\n| rev10Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"VM\">{{cite web|author=Matt O&#039;Leary |url=http://www.virginmedia.com/music/reviews/jimmyeatworld-chasethislight.php |title=Jimmy Eat World: Chase This Light review |publisher=[[Virgin Media]] |date=October 15, 2007 |accessdate=December 9, 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n''Chase This Light'' received generally positive reviews from [[Music journalism|music critic]]s. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album received an [[Weighted mean|average]] score of 66, based on 25 reviews.<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/> Andy Greenwald from ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave praise to the band for combining the \"extroverted guitar pop\" of ''[[Bleed American]]'' and the pensive bulk of ''[[Futures (album)|Futures]]'' to encapsulate what their given genre is: \"big emotions, sure, but also big hooks, big stakes. And big rewards.\" He concluded by calling ''Chase This Light'' \"a master class in hard rocking for the soft-hearted.\"<ref name=\"EW\"/> [[Slant Magazine]]'s Jonathan Keefe called it \"a return to form for the band in terms of their ingratiating power-pop\", praising the tracks \"Big Casino\" and \"Always Be\" for their instantly catchy instrumentation and melodies that make up the overall tone of the album. He added that \"it isn't a stretch to say that ''Chase This Light'' is one of the year\u2019s best power-pop records.\"<ref name=\"Slant\"/> ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' journalist Andrew Beaujon praised Jim Adkins' vocal delivery for having a \"youthful tang\" that sells the songs about \"getting older and maybe a little more cynical.\" He concluded that \"[T]he joy of ''Chase This Light'' is hearing him convince us that it comes back again, too.\"<ref name=\"Spin\"/>\n\n[[AllMusic]] editor Tim Sendra was ambivalent towards the record, commending the return to ''Bleed American'' material that's made up of \"rousing anthems (\"Big Casino\")\", \"melancholy rockers with singalong choruses (\"Chase This Light\")\" and \"sweet ballads (\"Dizzy\")\" but was critical of the dry and airless production, the vocals sounding passionless and the unimaginative lyricism, saying that its \"nice to listen to and vaguely uplifting, but ultimately empty on the inside.\" He concluded that \"Jimmy Eat World have proven they can do better than this and they may yet, but this album is a bit of a disappointment.\"<ref name=\"AM\"/> Andrew Blackie of ''[[PopMatters]]'' was also disappointed with the album coming across as \"a weaker, limper version\" of ''Futures'', criticizing producer Butch Vig for making the band sound \"processed and sterile\" and the lyrical content for being \"juvenile and sapped in self-important, happy-go-lucky sentiments.\" He concluded that \"[M]ore disappointing than that, though, is the fact that there is hardly anything groundbreaking to be found in ''Chase This Light''{{'}}s 40 minutes, which is less than we\u2019ve come to expect from this band.\"<ref name=\"PM\"/>\n\n===Commercial performance===\nThe album debuted at number five on the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart, selling approximately 62,000 copies in its first week.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hasty |first=Katie |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1047777/springsteen-returns-to-no-1-in-slow-sales-week |title=Springsteen Returns To No. 1 In Slow Sales Week |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=October 24, 2007 |accessdate=October 25, 2007}}</ref> It also sold 78,000 worldwide. As of July 2008, the album has sold approximately 320,000 copies worldwide, and, as of September 2010, the album has sold 225,000 copies in the United States (US).\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs written and composed by [[Jimmy Eat World]].\n{{Track list\n|title1 = [[Big Casino]] \n|length1 = 3:40\n|title2 = [[Let It Happen (Jimmy Eat World song)|Let It Happen]] \n|length2 = 3:25\n|title3 = [[Always Be]] \n|length3 = 3:04\n|title4 = Carry You \n|length4 = 4:22\n|title5 = Electable (Give It Up) \n|length5 = 2:56\n|title6 = Gotta Be Somebody's Blues \n|length6 = 4:46\n|title7 = Feeling Lucky \n|length7 = 2:32\n|title8 = Here It Goes \n|length8 = 3:26\n|title9 = [[Chase This Light (song)|Chase This Light]] \n|length9 = 3:29\n|title10 = Firefight \n|length10 = 3:53\n|title11 = Dizzy \n|length11 = 4:46\n}}\n;Bonus tracks\n* \"Be Sensible\" (Australia / UK / Germany / Japan / iTunes) \u2013 5:04\n* \"Distraction\" (Japan / UK/Best Buy US Bonus Download) \u2013 2:58\n* \"Open Bar Reception\" (Smartpunk/InSound pre-order) \u2013 3:55\n* \"Take 'Em as They Come\" ([[Bruce Springsteen]] cover) (iTunes pre-order) \u2013 3:55\n* \"Dizzy\" (acoustic) (iTunes) \u2013 4:27\n* \"Beautiful Is\" (Japan / UK Big Casino single/ Big Casino part 7\" vinyl) \u2013 2:30\n\n== Personnel ==\nAdapted credits from the booklet of ''Chase This Light''.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Chase This Light|others=Jimmy Eat World|year=2007|publisher=Interscope|type=booklet|id=B000992402}}</ref>\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Jimmy Eat World\n* Jim Adkins \u2013 lead vocals, guitar\n* Tom Linton \u2013 guitar, vocals\n* Zach Lind \u2013 drums, percussion\n* Rick Burch \u2013 bass, vocals\n\n;Additional musicians\n* Keith Armstrong \u2013 Assistant\n* [[David Campbell (arranger/composer)|David Campbell]] \u2013 Conductor, String Arrangements\n* [[John Fields (producer)|John Fields]] \u2013 Bass, Keyboards\n* Eva Lind \u2013 Vocals\n* Stephen Lu \u2013 Keyboards\n* Amy Ross \u2013 Vocals\n{{col-2}}\n;Production\n* Davies \u2013 Cover Photo\n* John Fields \u2013 Producer, Engineer\n* Ross Hogarth \u2013 Engineer\n* Ted Jensen \u2013 Mastering\n* Jimmy Eat World \u2013 Producer, Engineer\n* Chris Lord-Alge \u2013 Mixing\n* [[Christopher Mario Testa|Chris Testa]] \u2013 Producer, Engineer\n* Butch Vig \u2013 Executive Producer\n* Luke Wood \u2013 A&R\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Chart performance==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Chart (2007) !! Peak<br>position\n|-\n|{{albumchart|Billboard200|5|artist=Jimmy Eat World|artistid=304685}}\n|-\n|{{albumchart|BillboardAlternative|2|artist=Jimmy Eat World|artistid=304685}}\n|-\n|{{albumchart|BillboardRock|3|artist=Jimmy Eat World|artistid=304685}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- This is a licensed stream for the album, which is allowed under Wikipedia polices -->\n*[https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLmrRAbUdPIYH7vuup25QuIrs3Clf5NlpY ''Chase This Light''] at [[YouTube]] (streamed copy where licensed)\n*{{metacritic album|chase-this-light}}\n\n{{Jimmy Eat World}}\n\n[[Category:2007 albums]]\n[[Category:Jimmy Eat World albums]]\n[[Category:Albums arranged by David Campbell (composer)]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Butch Vig]]\n[[Category:Interscope Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use American English|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Chase This Light\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Jimmy Eat World]]\n| cover      = Chasethislight.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 16, 2007\n| recorded   = July 2006 \u2013 June 2007\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Alternative rock]]\n* [[emo]]\n* [[power pop]]\n* [[pop punk]]\n* [[pop rock]]\n}}\n| length     = 40:18\n| label      = [[Interscope Records|Interscope]]\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n* [[Jimmy Eat World]]\n* [[Christopher Mario Testa|Chris Testa]]\n* [[Butch Vig]]\n* [[John Fields (producer)|John Fields]] <small>(\"Here It Goes\")</small>\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Stay on My Side Tonight]]\n| prev_year  = 2005\n| next_title = [[Invented (album)|Invented]]\n| next_year  = 2010\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Chase This Light\n | type        = Studio\n | single1     = [[Big Casino]]\n | single1date = August 28, 2007\n | single2     = [[Always Be]]\n | single2date = December 3, 2007\n | single3     = Let It Happen\n | single3date = April 8, 2008\n}}\n}}\n'''''Chase This Light''''' is the sixth studio album by American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Jimmy Eat World]], released on October 16, 2007 by [[Interscope Records]]. The album was executive produced by [[Butch Vig]].\n\n==Recording==\nRecording for ''Chase This Light'' began in July 2006 with producer [[Butch Vig]]. In June 2007, it was announced that the album was being mixed by [[Chris Lord-Alge]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2131|title=Jimmy Eat World title new album, begin mixing|work=Alternative Press|date=June 5, 2007|accessdate=August 21, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160828101740/http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2131|archive-date=August 28, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\nThe song \"Carry You\" originated as a track from [[Jim Adkins]]' side project Go Big Casino.<ref>{{cite web|title=Has it really been 6 years?|url=http://gobigcasino.net/|work=Go Big Casino|publisher=GoBigCasino.net|accessdate=September 1, 2012|author=akatimo|date=May 27, 2012}}</ref><ref name=COS>{{cite web |author=Justin Gerber|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2013/06/dissected-jimmy-eat-world-with-jim-adkins/7/|title=Dissected: Jimmy Eat World (with Jim Adkins)|work=Consequence of Sound|page=7|accessdate=May 10, 2015}}</ref> Jimmy Eat World has recorded other Go Big Casino songs previously like \"[[Bleed American|Hear You Me]]\", \"[[Bleed American|My Sundown]]\", and \"Drugs or Me\".<ref>{{cite web|title=FAQ|url=http://gobigcasino.net/|work=GoBigCasino.net|publisher=GoBigCasino.net|accessdate=September 1, 2012|author=GoBigCasino.net|year=2004\u20132012}}</ref>\n\nAfter releasing \"Be Sensible\" as a B-Side, the band regretted not including it on the full album<ref>{{Citation|title=#41 - Zach and Holly Lind (The Wretched Desert, Jimmy Eat World)|url=https://open.spotify.com/episode/4ebCxWFka2AufHJKAVOqj4|language=en|access-date=2019-09-05}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nIn July 2007, the band went on a tour of the US, before doing several shows in South Africa as well as appearing at several festival dates in Europe the following month.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2295|title=Jimmy Eat World announce touring plans|work=Alternative Press|date=July 11, 2007|accessdate=August 25, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160828234349/http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2295|archive-date=August 28, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> On August 16, the album's track listing was revealed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2509|title=Jimmy Eat World reveal track listing|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=August 16, 2007|accessdate=March 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319023238/http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2509|archive-date=March 19, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> \"[[Big Casino]]\", the first single from the album, was released August 28 for download.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stereogum.com/6257/new_jimmy_eat_world_big_casino/video/|title=New Jimmy Eat World \u2013 \"Big Casino\"|work=Stereogum|accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref> The album's artwork was released the following day.<ref name=stereogumartwork>{{cite web|url=http://www.stereogum.com/6277/jimmy_eat_worlds_chase_this_light_album_art/news/|title=Jimmy Eat World's Chase This Light Album Art|work=Stereogum|accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref> In September and October, the group went on a North American tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2573|title=Jimmy Eat World to tour this fall|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=August 28, 2007|accessdate=March 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319022712/http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2573|archive-date=March 19, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''Chase This Light'' was released on October 16 through [[Interscope Records|Interscope]].<ref name=stereogumartwork/> A music video was released for \"Big Casino\" on October 24.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stereogum.com/6911/new_jimmy_eat_world_video_big_casino/video/|title=New Jimmy Eat World Video \u2013 \"Big Casino\"|work=Stereogum|accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref> \"[[Always Be (song)|Always Be]]\" began airing on various [[Radio channel#Audio|radio channels]] on December 3, 2007. In January 2008, the band supported [[Foo Fighters]] on a few US shows.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_3190|title=Jimmy Eat World to join Foo Fighters' 2008 U.S. tour|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=December 12, 2007|accessdate=July 8, 2017}}</ref> A music video for \"Always Be\" was released on January 29.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stereogum.com/7904/new_jimmy_eat_world_video_always_be/video/|title=New Jimmy Eat World Video \u2013 \"Always Be\"|work=Stereogum|accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref> From late January to early March, the band went on a tour of Europe and the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_2938|title=Jimmy Eat World plan U.K./European tour for early 2008|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=November 2, 2007|accessdate=July 8, 2017}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> They were supported by [[Styrofoam (musician)|Styrofoam]] on the latter part of the tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_3422|title=Jimmy Eat World frontman sings on new Styrofoam song|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=January 31, 2008|accessdate=July 8, 2017}}{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In early April, the band appeared at the [[Bamboozle Left]] festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_3511|title=Blaqk Audio, Hot Water Music, H2O added to Bamboozle Left|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=February 15, 2008|accessdate=July 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728175351/http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_3511#|archive-date=July 28, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \"Let It Happen\" was released to radio on April 8.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allaccess.com/mail/archive/eweekly/alternative/2008-4-1.html|title=AllAccess.com Alternative eWeekly|work=AllAccess|date=April 1, 2008|accessdate=July 2, 2016}}</ref> In April and May, the band went on a co-headlining US tour with [[Paramore]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_3508|title=Jimmy Eat World/Paramore dates announced|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=February 15, 2008|accessdate=July 9, 2017}}{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In June and July, the band went on a tour of North America<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_3854|title=Jimmy Eat World schedule Canada/U.S. dates for July|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=May 13, 2008|accessdate=July 10, 2017}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> with support from [[Dear and the Headlights]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/index.php/news/entry/archive_4067|title=Dear And The Headlights announce dates, complete recording|work=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press Magazine, Inc|date=June 12, 2008|accessdate=July 10, 2017}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical reception===\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = (66/100)<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/chase-this-light/jimmy-eat-world |title=Reviews for Chase This Light by Jimmy Eat World |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AbsolutePunk.net]] \n| rev1Score = (88%)<ref name=\"ABPunk\">{{cite web|last=Henderson |first=Steve |url=http://www.absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?t=271800 |title=Jimmy Eat World - Chase This Light - Album Review |publisher=AbsolutePunk.net |date=October 16, 2007 |accessdate=December 9, 2011 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120716112135/http://www.absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?t=271800 |archivedate=July 16, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref>\n| rev2 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web|last=Sendra |first=Tim |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/chase-this-light-mw0000486263 |title=Chase This Light - Jimmy Eat World |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=December 9, 2011}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3Score = A<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite magazine|last=Greenwald |first=Andy |url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20151945,00.html |title=Chase This Light Review |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |publisher=[[Time Inc.]] |date=October 12, 2007 |accessdate=December 9, 2011}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev4Score = (7/10)<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite magazine|last=Martin |first=Daniel |url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/jimmy-eat-world/9118 |title=NME Album Reviews - Jimmy Eat World |magazine=[[NME]] |publisher=[[IPC Media]] |date=October 19, 2007 |accessdate=December 9, 2011}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[PopMatters]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|5|10}}<ref name=\"PM\">{{cite web|last=Blackie |first=Andrew |url=https://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/jimmy-eat-world-chase-this-light/ |title=Jimmy Eat World: Chase This Light |website=[[PopMatters]] |date=October 16, 2007 |accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev6 = Rockfeedback\n| rev6Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Tomiak |first=Matt |url=http://www.rockfeedback.com/article.asp?nObjectID=5140 |title=Jimmy Eat World - Chase This Light |publisher=Rockfeedback |date=November 14, 2007 |accessdate=December 9, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090210064628/http://www.rockfeedback.com/article.asp?nObjectID=5140 |archivedate=February 10, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/16684805/review/16695742/chase_this_light |title=Chase This Light : Jimmy Eat World : Review |last=Hiatt |first=Brian |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |publisher=[[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media]] |date=October 18, 2007 |accessdate=April 4, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011024829/http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/16684805/review/16695742/chase_this_light |archivedate=October 11, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref>\n| rev8 = [[Slant Magazine]]\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"Slant\">{{cite web|last=Keefe |first=Jonathan |url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/jimmy-eat-world-chase-this-light/1198 |title=Jimmy Eat World: Chase This Light |publisher=[[Slant Magazine]] |date=October 15, 2007 |accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev9Score = (7/10)<ref name=\"Spin\">{{cite magazine|last=Beaujon |first=Andrew |url=https://www.spin.com/2007/11/jimmy-eat-world-chase-light-interscope/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090616152234/http://www.spin.com/reviews/jimmy-eat-world-chase-light-interscope|title=Jimmy Eat World, 'Chase This Light' (Interscope) |magazine=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |publisher=[[SpinMedia]] |date=November 1, 2007 |archivedate=June 16, 2009|accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev10 = [[Virgin Media]]\n| rev10Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"VM\">{{cite web|author=Matt O&#039;Leary |url=http://www.virginmedia.com/music/reviews/jimmyeatworld-chasethislight.php |title=Jimmy Eat World: Chase This Light review |publisher=[[Virgin Media]] |date=October 15, 2007 |accessdate=December 9, 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n''Chase This Light'' received generally positive reviews from [[Music journalism|music critic]]s. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album received an [[Weighted mean|average]] score of 66, based on 25 reviews.<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/> Andy Greenwald from ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave praise to the band for combining the \"extroverted guitar pop\" of ''[[Bleed American]]'' and the pensive bulk of ''[[Futures (album)|Futures]]'' to encapsulate what their given genre is: \"big emotions, sure, but also big hooks, big stakes. And big rewards.\" He concluded by calling ''Chase This Light'' \"a master class in hard rocking for the soft-hearted.\"<ref name=\"EW\"/> [[Slant Magazine]]'s Jonathan Keefe called it \"a return to form for the band in terms of their ingratiating power-pop\", praising the tracks \"Big Casino\" and \"Always Be\" for their instantly catchy instrumentation and melodies that make up the overall tone of the album. He added that \"it isn't a stretch to say that ''Chase This Light'' is one of the year\u2019s best power-pop records.\"<ref name=\"Slant\"/> ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' journalist Andrew Beaujon praised Jim Adkins' vocal delivery for having a \"youthful tang\" that sells the songs about \"getting older and maybe a little more cynical.\" He concluded that \"[T]he joy of ''Chase This Light'' is hearing him convince us that it comes back again, too.\"<ref name=\"Spin\"/>\n\n[[AllMusic]] editor Tim Sendra was ambivalent towards the record, commending the return to ''Bleed American'' material that's made up of \"rousing anthems (\"Big Casino\")\", \"melancholy rockers with singalong choruses (\"Chase This Light\")\" and \"sweet ballads (\"Dizzy\")\" but was critical of the dry and airless production, the vocals sounding passionless and the unimaginative lyricism, saying that its \"nice to listen to and vaguely uplifting, but ultimately empty on the inside.\" He concluded that \"Jimmy Eat World have proven they can do better than this and they may yet, but this album is a bit of a disappointment.\"<ref name=\"AM\"/> Andrew Blackie of ''[[PopMatters]]'' was also disappointed with the album coming across as \"a weaker, limper version\" of ''Futures'', criticizing producer Butch Vig for making the band sound \"processed and sterile\" and the lyrical content for being \"juvenile and sapped in self-important, happy-go-lucky sentiments.\" He concluded that \"[M]ore disappointing than that, though, is the fact that there is hardly anything groundbreaking to be found in ''Chase This Light''{{'}}s 40 minutes, which is less than we\u2019ve come to expect from this band.\"<ref name=\"PM\"/>\n\n===Commercial performance===\nThe album debuted at number five on the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart, selling approximately 62,000 copies in its first week.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hasty |first=Katie |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1047777/springsteen-returns-to-no-1-in-slow-sales-week |title=Springsteen Returns To No. 1 In Slow Sales Week |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=October 24, 2007 |accessdate=October 25, 2007}}</ref> It also sold 78,000 worldwide. As of July 2008, the album has sold approximately 320,000 copies worldwide, and, as of September 2010, the album has sold 225,000 copies in the United States (US).\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs written and composed by [[Jimmy Eat World]].\n{{Track list\n|title1 = [[Big Casino]] \n|length1 = 3:40\n|title2 = [[Let It Happen (Jimmy Eat World song)|Let It Happen]] \n|length2 = 3:25\n|title3 = [[Always Be]] \n|length3 = 3:04\n|title4 = Carry You \n|length4 = 4:22\n|title5 = Electable (Give It Up) \n|length5 = 2:56\n|title6 = Gotta Be Somebody's Blues \n|length6 = 4:46\n|title7 = Feeling Lucky \n|length7 = 2:32\n|title8 = Here It Goes \n|length8 = 3:26\n|title9 = [[Chase This Light (song)|Chase This Light]] \n|length9 = 3:29\n|title10 = Firefight \n|length10 = 3:53\n|title11 = Dizzy \n|length11 = 4:46\n}}\n;Bonus tracks\n* \"Be Sensible\" (Australia / UK / Germany / Japan / iTunes) \u2013 5:04\n* \"Distraction\" (Japan / UK/Best Buy US Bonus Download) \u2013 2:58\n* \"Open Bar Reception\" (Smartpunk/InSound pre-order) \u2013 3:55\n* \"Take 'Em as They Come\" ([[Bruce Springsteen]] cover) (iTunes pre-order) \u2013 3:55\n* \"Dizzy\" (acoustic) (iTunes) \u2013 4:27\n* \"Beautiful Is\" (Japan / UK Big Casino single/ Big Casino part 7\" vinyl) \u2013 2:30\n\n== Personnel ==\nAdapted credits from the booklet of ''Chase This Light''.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Chase This Light|others=Jimmy Eat World|year=2007|publisher=Interscope|type=booklet|id=B000992402}}</ref>\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Jimmy Eat World\n* Jim Adkins \u2013 lead vocals, guitar\n* Tom Linton \u2013 guitar, vocals\n* Zach Lind \u2013 drums, percussion\n* Rick Burch \u2013 bass, vocals\n\n;Additional musicians\n* Keith Armstrong \u2013 Assistant\n* [[David Campbell (arranger/composer)|David Campbell]] \u2013 Conductor, String Arrangements\n* [[John Fields (producer)|John Fields]] \u2013 Bass, Keyboards\